{
  "metadata": {
    "anchor_id": "member_a",
    "description": "58-year-old female, HMO plan. Chronic condition arc (hypertension + Type 2 Diabetes) — rising A1C, ER hypertensive crisis, cardiology workup, care management enrollment, GLP-1 therapy success. Jan–Dec 2025 longitudinal narrative.",
    "created": "2026-03-06",
    "narrative_summary": "Dorothy Williams is a 58-year-old woman in New York managing Type 2 Diabetes and Hypertension on an HMO plan. At her January 2025 wellness visit, her A1C was 8.2% (above target) and blood pressure was uncontrolled. Her PCP referred her to endocrinology, and Jardiance was added to her regimen. In May she presented to the ER with a hypertensive crisis (BP 210/125), was stabilized and discharged with Lisinopril added. A cardiology workup found mild left ventricular hypertrophy. By June her A1C had risen to 8.5% despite Jardiance, so her endocrinologist recommended Ozempic (GLP-1). The prior auth was approved (step therapy satisfied via Jardiance trial). She was enrolled in care management for chronic conditions. By October her A1C improved to 7.2%, and by her December annual wellness it was 6.8% (at target) with blood pressure well-controlled."
  },

